  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Money Laundering Suppression Act of 1994\n\n2. Key Federal Provisions:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Money laundering criminal offenses)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (Monetary transactions in criminally derived property)\n\n3. State-Level Statutes:\nMany states have their own money laundering laws that complement federal statutes\n\n4. International Cooperation:\n- The U.S. works with international organizations like FATF (Financial Action Task Force)\n\nThese statutes generally:\n- Criminalize financial transactions involving proceeds from illegal activities\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Establish reporting requirements for large cash transactions\n- Impose penalties including fines and imprisonment\n- Provide mechanisms for asset forfeiture\n\nThe primary goal of these laws is to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income.",
